metadata.name: This is the lie  #1
metadata.description:
The Project of the Nameless Sheep stems from an artistic and provocative necessity that aims to conceptually unite the Orwellian philosophy of 1984 with the thoughts of the great master Modigliani. The latter once stated, "I shall paint your eyes only when I know your soul."

The collection is a cry of disagreement towards destructive and uncontrollable globalization. It draws inspiration from an impersonal observation of modern society, critically examining historical events, corporations, and notable figures who have sold their soul for individualistic power that disregards the lives of others and the environment.

An ever-evolving project that will mature its search for soulless bodies over time.

1984 token, at a price as provocative as the theme of the collection.

Any reference to individuals, things or concepts is entirely coincidental and generated by a hash.

metadata.name: cosmic circles #23
metadata.description:
'cosmic circles' is a geometric representation of cosmic phenomena.

Iterations undergoing an eclipse contain a larger circle casting its shadow upon the grid. The grid itself contains planets orbiting suns, dwarf planets, stars or sun rays.

5% chance of sun rays, 50% chance of an eclipse.
6 colour palettes.


100% code (p5.js)

metadata.name: Skravert #127
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS #352
metadata.description:
EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS

after symbol 2525, 
aint gonna need to load, write no code
everything you think, do and say
is in the streams that you watch today (oh oh oh)

We find this code is very much alive. They are epi. They are hyper. They are derp. They are flardioids.

Epihyperderpflardioids is the name I have given to a large family of symmetrical loopy shapes, based on sine waves and rotations, reminiscent of the mathematical toy game "Spirograph", but also different. I studied them extensively, but don't claim to understand them fully, yet. I hope you enjoy them as much as I do.

These 365 Epihyperderpflardioids were generated for FXhash's one year anniversary.

metadata.name: Angular View #22
metadata.description:
The angle factor plays a significant role in determining how an image feels and looks.
When viewed from one angle, elements inside the frame might appear compressed and unclear, while when viewed from another angle, they might appear clear and distinct.
Choosing the right angle can encourage and guide the audience, while choosing the wrong angle can confuse and mislead him.
Therefore, when choosing the angle, one should consider aesthetic, technical, and emotional factors to present the subject to the viewer in the best light.
Depending on the angle, space and subject of the image are transformed and they can convey various meanings, including: logical visualization of space/impossible and free visualization, exaggeration and exaggeration/simplicity, stillness/movement, insider/alienation, mysterious/reliable, and complexity.
Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Livro #114
metadata.description:
A messy book is a well-read book, a sign of knowledge acquired. It's easy to spot a book that has been loved and used frequently. The pages are bent and creased, the spine is worn, and notes are scribbled in the margins. These imperfections are not a sign of neglect or carelessness, but rather an evidence of a book that has been fully engaged with and understood.
A book that is kept in pristine condition may look nice on a shelf, but it is also a sign that it has not been read as much, or not as deeply. A well-read book is an indication of a curious and active mind, always seeking to learn and grow. So, don't be afraid to let your books get a little messy, it's a sign that you're gaining knowledge and expanding your understanding of the world around you.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love <3

[S] to save as image

metadata.name: Here When You Need Me #238
metadata.description:
'Here When You Need Me' is a generative system that creates...

Good question, and I think the answer is up to you. Jewels? Reflections? The Sand in a Life's Hourglass?

Who knows. The truth is that I didn't have anything in mind for the project, and where it has ended up was purely through exploration, and a refinement of simple methods.

By the end, it has become exactly what I needed it to be, and the results of this project give me an encouragement that is difficult to explain.

Now, one of the primary features of the project is your ability to make it what you need. Several URL arguments are explained below that will allow you to tweak your edition's distortion and resolution.

15% of primary sales will be donated to 'Girls Who Code'
15% of primary sales will be donated to 'Cure Parkinson's'

10% of royalties will go to 'Girls Who Code'
10% of royalties will go to 'Cure Parkinson's'
10% of royalties will go to the original minter

Thank you everyone.


Options
-------
Parameters can be appended to the live URL to adjust the output's distortion, resolution, border size, and border color. These are all fun to play with, and can be used in combination to showcase the variability and potential of each piece.

'&distortion=#': Adjust distortion, any value from 0.0 to 3.0 (Use 0 to see a 'flat' version of the image)
'&resolution=#': Multiplier for width/height, any value from 0.1 to 6.0 (Soft max of 3.9)
'&borderSize=#': Multiplier for border size, any value from 0.0 to 3.0 (Use 0 for no border)
'&borderColor=ffffff': Custom border color, any 6 character hex code (Do not include '#')

An example of using multiple options would be '&resolution=2&distortion=.5'

Please check the linked fx(text) article for detailed examples on using these options.


Distortion
----------
I wanted to provide some amount of control to take advantage of the possibilities of generative art. 'Here When You Need Me' starts off at a certain point, but allows you to adjust the distortion to your favorite level.

Using '&distortion=0' will show the underlying shapes.


Resolution / Printing
---------------------
'Here When You Need Me' looks best with at least '&resolution=2' and is designed to support printing. Remember that parameters can be provided to adjust the border attributes as well.

Ideally, you should aim for 300 'pixels per inch' for a decent quality print. Default resolution is 1800x2400.

'&resolution=1' -> 6"x8"
'&resolution=2' -> 12"x16"

Some quick math will give you the correct modifier if you start with the width in inches of your desired print. 

(inches) * (ppi) / (default width)

An important note, the maximum resolution modifier I've had success with is 3.9 because of the browser's image size limitations, but the capability is still in the code to go higher in case it is helpful to someone.

If you have your edition printed, please share with me because it would make me incredibly happy to see it!


---------
Thank you to everyone for your support and contributions. 

I put way more detail in this description than I intended, but if you want even more, you can read about the development and potential of this project in the accompanying fx(text) article, once it is written.

Created by Walter Anderson (@noxiarb)

metadata.name: Forgive Your Sins #3
metadata.description:
This is a colorful remix for #genuary32nd of my late #genuary23 work done on 31st of January!
This is my tribute to Yayoi Kusama (#genuary25) with viscous dots of digital ink thrown in digital liquid and then shaken by digital sine waves (#genuary15) inspired by marbling techniques.

This is the 2nd iteration of my Wasm/Rust fluid simulation engine after "Viscous Circles" collection. Check it on FxHash if you want to know more about the engine behind this generator.

Controls

You can stop at any step if you like the state at this instant, you can restart it, de/increase resolution (default is 4096x4096 to have sharp image, up to 16K x 16K) and snapshot at any resolution.

- H: hide/show help.
- Space - pause/start animation.
- R - restart animation.
- I - hide/show res/fps panel.
- A-Q/D - down/up full resolution
- S - take full resolution snapshot

Now, forgive your sins!

Forgive Your Sins @naibdian 2023 Project made using Opensource WebGL, WASM/Rust/JS libs
#genuary32nd #genuary23 #genuary15 #genuary25

metadata.description:
"Symphony of fxhash" is an animated work that tries to convey feelings.
There are 10 albums in this work. The owners of the albums are the artists who had the most marketplace during the last 7 days.
Each album has about 5 tracks. These tracks are the last 5 works of the artists of the album (there are also artists who had less than 5 works, in this case all their works are included).

metadata.name: The Woodcarver's apprentice #19
metadata.description:
A mix of aesthetics from the Ukiyo-e and Shin-hanga woodblock movements, with modern elements.  

ukiyo-e (浮世絵) = "pictures of the floating world", which peaked in the late 19th century. 
shin-hanga (新版画) = "new prints", from roughly the 1920-1950s. 

Some comparisons between the prints of the Japanese masters and gen-art: 

* The number of prints. Based on how well a piece was received, the publisher could decide to produce more copies, usually in batches of 200. Compare this to limiting the edition size on fx(hash). The initial prints would have sharp lines and accurately coloured areas. Very popular prints with thousands of impressions would slowly degrade the blocks, leaving final prints with worn-out linework and colours that weren't true to originals.  

* Woodblock prints were actually a collab between the artist, the wood carver, and the printer. In many cases only the artist and publisher were recognized on the final prints. It was usually the publisher who owned the woodblock, not the artist. Often the artist was considered a worker, contracted at the request of the publisher or patrons funding the project. Compare this to the NFT space, where ownership is carved onto the blockchain, and artists have freedom to create whatever they wish. 

* Copyminters.... Similar to the NFT world, fake publishers sprang up from time to time, who would reproduce famous prints. Enji Takamizawa was one such counterfeiter, who was able to skilfully produce woodblocks replicating originals down to the wood grain! 

* While fine-quality woodblock prints from the Edo era command huge auction prices today, they were in reality affordable art for the regular people of their time. NFTs are similar in this light, where we can enjoy pieces at home rather than say, visiting galleries or museums of unattainable art. 



Additional querystring params (use when viewing in a separate window) 

* fullsize=true (33 megapixel output) 
* colourcorrect=false 
* grain=false 
* border=false 



Licenses included in source. Relying on: 

* PIXIJS for drawing 
* JSTS for geometry functions 
* chromajs for colour functions 
* noise and gaussian helpers from p5js
